&gt; When using the TestSetup decorator, Implementing oneTimeSetUp() is not
&gt; absolutely essential, but why would you want to use the test decorator
&gt; unless oneTimeSetUp was your aim?
&gt; 
&gt; The main point of the TestSetup decorator is to provide the ability to
&gt; perform one-time setup and teardown, i.e. oneTimeSetUp() is 
&gt; run once before
&gt; all of your tests (not each, but all), and oneTimeTearDown() 
&gt; is run once
&gt; after all of your tests complete.  If you don&#39;t need this 
&gt; functionality,
&gt; then you don&#39;t need the TestSetup decorator.  You may remove 
&gt; the following
&gt; code from your suite() method:
&gt;     TestSetup wrapper = new TestSetup(suite) {
&gt;         public void setUp () {
&gt;             oneTimeSetUp();
&gt;         }
&gt; and have it return suite instead of the TestSetup that it 
&gt; currently returns.
&gt; 
